***************************************************************************
                              Naming and Descriptions
***************************************************************************
Note: All literal code in this help document is separated by a bunch of =
signs. The = signs are NOT part of the code. For example:

====================
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
#include <material.h>
====================

refers to the three include lines, literally.


***************************************************************************
                              Naming/Desc Basics
***************************************************************************

All monster, weapons, armors, and other objects have names. These names
are how players and the mudlib refer to the items. Visible objects also
have descriptions. These descriptions are how players see these objects.
(NOTE: rooms also have descriptions, but not names) The reason for this
document is to spell out exactly how to use names in a consistent manner.

The following function calls can be used to set the name(s) of an object:

====================
set_name(string sName);
set_alias(string sAlias);
set_aliases(string* asAliases);
====================

set_name() is used to set the primary name of an object. The primary
name of an object may occasionally be shown to a player under certain
circumstance. Each object can only have one primary name, and the
object can be referred to by that name, by players (for looking etc).

set_alias() is used to set an alias name of an object. The alias name
never appears to the player, but can be used by the player to refer to
an object. Multiple calls to set_alias() can be used to set multiple
aliases.

set_aliases() is used to set multiple aliases at once. Note that this
will clear all previously set aliases.


The following function calls can be used to set the desc(s) of an object:

====================
set_long(string sLong);
set_short(string sShort);
set_short_modifier(string sMod);
set_short_modifiers(string* asMod);
====================

set_long() is used to set the long desc of an object. This desc is what
is seen when the object is looked at. The long desc in a room is what is
seen when a player enters a room with brief mode off.

set_short() is used to set the short desc of an object. This desc is what
is seen when the player doesn't actually look specifically at the object
(for example, a player's inventory lists things by short desc). In rooms,
the short desc is what is seen when the player is in brief mode.

set_short_modifier() and set_short_modifiers() work in the same was as
aliases. Short modifiers alter the short desc line of an object by adding
the modifier string in brackets.


***************************************************************************
                              Deprecated Functions
***************************************************************************

The following functions are deprecated and should no longer be used. Older
code may contain them, and they will still work, but they should not be
used in new code:

====================
set_id(string sId);                // same as set_name
reset_short(string sShort);        // same as set_short
add_alias(string sAlias);          // same as set_alias
set_alt_name(string sAltName);     // same as set_alias
====================



***************************************************************************
                              Names
***************************************************************************

The name is the main name of an object, and should be something obvious
for that item. It should be all-lowercase, except for proper names, and
not contain any articles such as 'the' or 'a'.

Alias names are other names that may refer to the object. They should
always be all lowercase, with no articles. Try to include aliases for
all reasonable combinations of an object's short desc, or obvious
characteristics. (E.g. a rapier should have a 'sword' alias)

In some cases, it is useful for an object to have special aliases so that
other code can recognize that that particular object from other, similar
ones (Like a special quest sword). In these cases, add a unique alias
(not used anywhere else on the mud) that starts with double underscores
and the coder's name. E.g. __bob_dwarf_mines_key.


***************************************************************************
                              Descriptions
***************************************************************************

Short descs should be short (one line) descriptions of the object. This
can be considered a first impression upon seeing it, but it can also
be used to give extra implied information. For example:

    gleaming longsword
    large goblin
    Ed the horse

are all good short descs. Note that all short descs should be entirely
in lowercase letters except for proper names which start with a capital.
Do not use articles like 'the' or 'a' in the short desc. (Exception:
the short desc for rooms may use articles, and are always first letter
capped). N.B. The ENTIRE short desc can be used to refer to an object
as well. There is no need to make a separate alias for it.

Long descs are a detailed description seen when a player looks at an
object/room in detail. Long descs should be in complete English
sentences, with appropriate punctuation and capitalization.

Short modifiers should be words/short phrases that briefly denote how
an object has been modified. For example:

    hardened
    chipped
    broken
    poisoned

are all good modifiers.


***************************************************************************
                              Using Names/Descs
***************************************************************************

Sometimes, the name/descs are are used in spam and for other uses in the
course of building. There are appropriate queries for each kind of name
and desc, and some extras as well. If you need this functionality, this
is all encapsulated in the alias.c inherit. If you do not have permissions
to read this file, ask an ARCH+.


